==English==

===Etymology===
Existing since the thirteenth century: from {{etyl|fro}} ''[[envie#French|envie]]'', from {{etyl|la}} ''[[invidia#Latin|invidia]]'', from ''[[invidere#Latin|invidere]]'', “look at with [[malice]]”.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{enPR|ĕn'vē}}, {{IPA|/ˈɛnviː/}}, {{SAMPA|/"Envi:/}}
* {{audio|En-us-envy.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|envies|-}}

# [[resentful|Resentful]] desire of something possessed by another or others (but not limited to material possessions); as distinct from [[jealousy]].
#* '''1983'''.  ROSEN, Stanley.  ''Plato’s'' Sophist.  p. 66.
#*: Theodorus assures Socrates that no '''envy''' will prevent the Stranger from responding

